"title": "7430: Sabbath, in NT",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "7430",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>The NT develops the OT teaching on the Sabbath in three important directions. It declares that the Sabbath should not be observed in a legalistic manner; the Sabbath-rest is treated as an important symbol of the Christian doctrine of salvation; and finally, the NT itself indicates how Sunday, rather than Saturday, came to be seen as the Christian Sabbath.</p>\n<h2>Gospel incidents connected with the Sabbath</h2>\n<h3>Exorcism</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:21-Mark1:25\">MRK 1:21–1:25</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke4:31-Luke4:35\">LUK 4:31–4:35</a></p>\n<h3>Healing</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt12:9-Matt12:14\">MAT 12:9–12:14</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark3:1-Mark3:6\">MRK 3:1–3:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke6:6-Luke6:11\">LUK 6:6–6:11</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:30-Mark1:31\">MRK 1:30–1:31</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke4:38-Luke4:40\">LUK 4:38–4:40</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke13:10-Luke13:17\">LUK 13:10–13:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke14:1-Luke14:6\">LUK 14:1–14:6</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John5:5-John5:18\">JHN 5:5–5:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John9:1-John9:16\">JHN 9:1–9:16</a></p>\n<h3>Teaching</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark6:2\">MRK 6:2</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt13:54\">MAT 13:54</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke4:16\">LUK 4:16</a></p>\n<h3>Other references</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt28:1\">MAT 28:1</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark16:1\">MRK 16:1</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke23:55-Luke23:56\">LUK 23:55–23:56</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John12:2\">JHN 12:2</a></p>\n<h2>Jesus Christ's teaching regarding the Sabbath</h2>\n<h3>Jesus Christ observes the Sabbath regulation</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke4:16\">LUK 4:16</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt24:20\">MAT 24:20</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts1:12\">ACT 1:12</a></p>\n<h3>Human well-being is more important than rigid observance of the Law</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark2:27-Mark2:28\">MRK 2:27–2:28</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt12:3\">MAT 12:3</a></p>\n<h3>Ceremonial observance must give way before any higher, or more spiritual, motive</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt12:5-Matt12:6\">MAT 12:5–12:6</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke6:5\">LUK 6:5</a></p>\n<h2>Sabbath reading of Scripture provided an opportunity for reaching the Jews</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts17:2\">ACT 17:2</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts13:14\">ACT 13:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts13:27\">ACT 13:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts13:42\">ACT 13:42</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts13:44\">ACT 13:44</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts15:21\">ACT 15:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts16:13\">ACT 16:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts18:4\">ACT 18:4</a></p>\n<h2>Sabbath observance was optional for Gentile Christians</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Col2:16\">COL 2:16</a></strong></p>\n<h2>The Lord's Day</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev1:10\">REV 1:10</a></strong> <em>At an early stage the Sabbath was replaced by Sunday (the first day of the week) as the day for rest and worship.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John20:19\">JHN 20:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John20:26\">JHN 20:26</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts20:7\">ACT 20:7</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor16:2\">1CO 16:2</a></p>\n<h2>The Sabbath-rest is seen as a symbol of the salvation of the people of God</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb4:1\">HEB 4:1</a></strong> <em>The OT promise of rest was unfulfilled, on account of Israel's disobedience</em>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb3:18-Heb3:19\">HEB 3:18–3:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb4:9\">HEB 4:9</a></strong> <em>The OT promise of rest remains open.</em></p>",
